Url sound sources and ambiences.

A url source and a url ambience both play streamed audio from a web address — an internet radio stream or a direct link to an audio file online — instead of from the map's own sound folders. They're the only builder objects that pull their sound live from the internet, which makes them the way to drop a real radio station, a podcast feed, or any hosted track into a map. The two are built and configured exactly alike; the one thing that sets them apart is when the stream plays, which is covered below.

How a url object works.

Both take a web address and play it as a looping, positioned sound somewhere on the map, at a volume and pitch you choose. Either can be built as a single point or a ranged area. A single one emits from one exact tile with normal distance falloff, so it grows louder as the player approaches and quieter as they walk away. A ranged one fills its whole rectangle at full volume and fades only once the player passes beyond the edges. On 3d maps the area spans height as well, between its minimum and maximum z.

Because the audio comes from the internet rather than a packaged file, a url object needs a working connection to be heard, and it streams live — there's no clip stored in the map.

Source versus ambience.

The difference is whether the stream is always running or only runs while the player is present:

A url source plays continuously. It streams the whole time the map is loaded, whether or not the player is anywhere near, and the player simply hears it by proximity — louder up close, fainter at a distance. Walk away from a source and come back, and it will have moved on in the stream, because it never stopped. From outside a ranged source the player still hears the fading edge of it.
A url ambience plays only while the player is inside its area. The moment the player leaves its bounds the stream pauses, and it resumes from where it left off when they step back in. From outside an ambience there is nothing to hear at all — it's silent until entered.

Reach for a source when the sound should live in the world continuously, like a radio left playing at a spot the player should hear as they approach. Reach for an ambience when the audio is background for a place and should only run while the player is actually there, picking up where it paused each time they return.

Url fields.

Both forms take the following:

Build mode. Single for one exact tile, or ranged for a rectangular area. Single is the default.

Coordinates. For a single url object, an x and a y (and a z on 3d maps) — the one tile it plays from. For a ranged url object, a minimum and maximum x and a minimum and maximum y (and a minimum and maximum z on 3d maps), marking the rectangle it fills.

Url. The web address of the stream or audio file to play. It can't contain spaces.

Volume. How loud the stream plays, from -100 at the quietest up to 0 at full volume.
Pitch. The playback pitch as a flat value, defaulting to 100 for the stream's natural pitch and ranging from 5 to 1000 — lower values play deeper and slower, higher values brighter and faster.

Auditioning sounds in the builder.

While the url box, the volume slider, or the pitch slider is focused in the form, press space to start a streaming preview of the address you've typed, and press space again to stop it. Adjusting the volume or pitch slider while the preview is playing updates it live, so you can set the level and pitch by ear before placing the object. The preview only plays once a url has been entered.

Authoring url objects by hand.

If you edit main.sif directly, a url source is written under the name url_source and a url ambience under the name url_ambience; everything else about the two lines is identical. A single one is url_source x y url volume pitch, and on 3d maps a z follows the y: url_source x y z url volume pitch. A ranged one is url_source minx maxx miny maxy url volume pitch, and on 3d maps a minimum and maximum z follow the y pair: url_source minx maxx miny maxy minz maxz url volume pitch. Each name covers both its single and ranged form — the line is read as ranged when it carries the extra coordinates. The url must contain no spaces, and the volume and pitch are numbers.
